Source: CNN Online, Tue 24 Sep 2002 [edited]
<http://www.cnn.com/2002/HEALTH/conditions/09/24/west.nile/index.html>


West Nile Virus Human Death toll Reaches 94: Joint Congressional Meeting
-------------------------------------------------
The number of deaths linked to West Nile virus infection in the United
States this year has risen to 94, and nearly 2000 people have been
diagnosed with it, federal health officials said on Tue 24 Sep 2002. On
Tuesday 2 congressional committees will hold a joint hearing to look into
the challenges the virus presents to public health. The panels will hear
from top health officials, including Dr. Julie Gerberding, Director of the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, and Dr. Anthony Fauci, director
of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases.

The CDC said on Tuesday that 1963 people have been diagnosed with West Nile
virus in the United States so far in 2002. Illinois has had the most
deaths, with 25. Louisiana and Michigan have had 11 each.

Health officials said they suspect tens of thousands of people nationwide
have contracted West Nile virus, but most cases are never diagnosed. Most
people experience few or no symptoms. About one in 150 people who contract
West Nile virus infection develops encephalitis or meningitis. Those cases
generally involve older people and those with weakened immune systems. In
those instances, the [infection] can prove fatal. Health officials also
have determined the virus can cause paralysis. Mosquitoes carry the virus,
but the CDC has said it appears likely that some people contracted West
Nile virus through organ transplants and blood transfusions. Blood banks
are taking special precautions to try to weed out donors who may have
symptoms of the virus.

--
Luz Alba Fornells, Ph.D.,
Center for the Study of Emerging Infectious Diseases
Dep.Medical Biochemistry, Institute of Biomedical Sciences,
Federal University of Rio de Janeiro, BRAZIL
