Second Long Island Resident Dies of West Nile Virus Infection
-----------------------------------------------
A 72-year-old Huntington man who was diagnosed with West Nile virus while
visiting Michigan in August 2002 died from the illness on 13 Sep 2002,
Suffolk County [New York state] health officials said yesterday. The man,
whose name was not released, was the second Long Islander to die from the
virus this year. The first, a Melville resident aged 81, died on 19 Aug
2002. There have been a total of 12 cases disclosed by health officials on
Long Island this year. Of those, 7 have been in Nassau and 5 in Suffolk.

The Huntington man's symptoms began on 17 Aug 2002, 2 days after he arrived
in Michigan, Suffolk Health Department spokeswoman Millie Dinda said
yesterday. It usually takes 5 to 15 days for symptoms to appear after a
person is infected, experts say. Before his trip to Michigan, he had
traveled to Boston and returned to Huntington on 4 Aug 2002, where he
stayed until 15 Aug 2002, Dinda said. The health department said it was not
possible to ascertain where he contracted the disease.

On 17 Aug 2002, he started developing symptoms, including confusion and
muscle weakness. By 30 Aug 2002, he had slipped into a coma, and he
remained in a coma in a Michigan hospital until he died on 13 Sep 2002.
Suffolk County officials initially announced the man's infection on 12 Sep
2002, when they incorrectly gave his age as 75. Dinda said yesterday that
the county health department did not learn of the man's death until 16 Sep
2002.

[Byline: Erik Holm]

