[4]
Date Wed 25 Sep 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Environmental Risk Analysis Program, Cornell University Center for
the Environment, Mon 23 Sep 2002 [edited]
<http://www.cfe.cornell.edu/erap/WNV/>


West Nile Virus Latest News as of Mon 23 Sep 2002
-----------------------------------------------
West Nile Virus (WNV) has crossed the continental divide: WNV has been
detected on both sides of the divide in Colorado and is confirmed in
California, on the Pacific Coast, and in Nova Scotia, Canada, on the
Atlantic coast. On Fri 20 Sep 2002, the Nova Scotia Department of Health
confirmed WNV in a blue jay found in Dartmouth, and announced a presumptive
positive crow found in Kingston on 26 Aug 2002. (These locations are NE of
Maine, the furthest east that WNV has been detected in North America,
approximately at the 65th meridian). Across the continent, the California
Department of Heath Services confirmed on 12 Sep 2002 that a woman from Los
Angeles Co was exposed to WNV in state. Ongoing surveillance throughout
California since 2000 had not detected WNV in mosquitoes, birds, or other
animals, the typical "early warnings" that have preceded detection of human
cases in other places. Since the woman has not recently travelled out of
state, her case is the first reported in California. It was first announced
6 Sep 2002 as "probable." In many states it has been detected in all, or
nearly all, counties.

The number of equine cases has seen an upsurge, with at least 5380 cases
reported to USDA APHIS by state health officials in 33 states as of 17 Sep
2002. This compares with 3453 cases reported from 30 states on 8 Sep 2002.
WNV has now been associated with illness and death in several other mammal
species, including squirrel, wolf and dog in Illinois (which leads the
country in number of human cases) and mountain goat and sheep in Nebraska
(which leads the country in numbers of equine cases). University of
Minnesota's Raptor Center reports increasing numbers of raptors picked up
sick or dead, infected with WNV but perhaps also with other confounding
disease.

Labor Day Weekend 2002 brought news of another risk related to WNV, with a
growing body of evidence that the virus can be transmitted via organ
transplant from an infected person (and an associated risk that it might
also be transmitted by blood transfusion). By end of the first week of
September 2002, the CDC confirmed with a high level of certainty that the
organs from an infected donor had transmitted the infection to 4 organ
recipients.

Research to determine if WNV can also be transmitted via blood transfusion
was prompted by trying to understand how the organ donor had become
infected, since blood tests before she received blood transfusions did not
show she was WNV-positive, while later tests did. Interest was spurred when
it was learned that at least 4 other people have been diagnosed with WNV
infection after receiving blood transfusions. Although
transfusion-associated transmission "is highly suspicious," the current
investigations involve people from areas with high levels of WNV activity,
so the evidence thus far is not conclusive. One of the 7 related
investigations detailed by CDC in the has shown that WNV can survive in
some blood components (likely for several days) and probably can be
transmitted by transfusion. Another of the investigations has shown that
not all recipients of WNV-contaminated units will become infected with WNV.

While evidence that WNV can be transmitted through blood transfusions adds
a wrinkle to the set of assumptions about disease transmission, the general
population is at no greater risk of contracting WNV than previously
thought. The news does make us aware that a sub-population of people about
to undergo high risk organ transplants and/or receive blood transfusions
(about 4.5 million persons in the US receive blood or blood products
annually) may be at still greater health risk due to the increased risk of
contracting WNV.

However, CDC health officials point out that the additional risk of
contracting WNV is quite small in comparison with the much larger risks
from these medical procedures. The process of donating blood poses no risk
to the blood donor for contracting WNV. Related to these investigations,
research is also underway to develop more rapid tests for determining
whether asymptomatic people are infected with WNV. Such a test could enable
screening for WNV in donated blood. However, in a 19 Sep 2002 press
briefing it was noted (a) that screening would be quite difficult because
there would be relatively small amounts of the virus in blood of an
asymptomatic infected person; and (b) it would be necessary to detect the
virus itself, not antibodies the body produces in response to infection.

The number of lab-positive human cases of WNV-associated illness is
continuing to increase in 2002, with CDC reporting 1963 confirmed or
probable cases as of Mon 23 Sep 2002 (94 fatalities) in 32 states (North
Carolina having reported its first-ever human case) and Washington DC. This
compares with 1745 cases (84 fatalities) in 31 states reported 19 Sep; 1295
cases (54 fatalities) in 30 states reported 12 Sep; 954 cases (43
fatalities) in 29 states reported 6 Sep; 737 cases (40 fatalities) in 28
states reported 4 Sep; 555 cases (28 fatalities) in 26 states reported 29
Aug; 480 cases (24 fatalities) in 22 states reported 28 Aug; 425 cases (20
fatalities) in 20 states reported 27 Aug; 371 cases (16 fatalities) in 20
states reported 23 Aug; 296 cases (14 fatalities) in 17 states reported 22
Aug; 210 cases reported 21 Aug; and 156 cases reported 14 Aug 2002.

